    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$89.5B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card negative">
      <div class="stat-value">-${Math.abs(actualFCF2025 / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY25 Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$6.0B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Normalized FCF (Model Base)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card negative">
      <div class="stat-value">-${Math.abs(netCash / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Debt</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">768M</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Shares Outstanding</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Turnaround DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model. However, because Boeing's current Free Cash Flow is negative (-$1.88B in FY2025), a standard DCF yields an invalid (negative) value. We must model a turnaround scenario by establishing a "normalized" base year.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Establish a Normalized Base FCF</h4>
      <p>Boeing generated negative $1.88 billion in FCF in FY2025 as it continues to recover from production halts, supply chain issues, and quality control crises. We assume a successful turnaround stabilizes operations, creating a normalized base FCF of <strong>$6.0 billion</strong> (Year 0 of our model). This represents Boeing's cash generation capability in a normal, functioning duopoly environment.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF recovery for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>From the normalized base, we project aggressive <strong>15% annual FCF growth</strong> for 5 years. This reflects recovering delivery volumes (737 MAX, 787), working capital improvements as inventory clears, and margin expansion as anomalous costs fall away.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume the recovery matures and FCF grows at <strong>3.0% forever</strong> — roughly matching long-term inflation and GDP growth. This reflects the reality of a mature, capital-intensive aerospace business.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount at a higher WACC</h4>
      <p>Due to Boeing's high debt load ($54.1B) and significant execution risk in its turnaround, we apply a high discount rate of <strong>12%</strong>. This demands a larger return to compensate investors for the uncertainty.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Subtract massive Net Debt</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value minus Net Debt ($24.7B) = Equity Value. Boeing's heavy debt burden significantly drags down the final per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Core Modeling Assumptions</h2>
  <p>Valuing a turnaround is inherently subjective. These three assumptions define our view of Boeing's recovery path.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">15%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Starting from a $6B base, 15% growth implies FCF reaches ~$12B by Year 5. This requires Boeing to consistently deliver 50+ 737s and 10 787s per month, clear stored inventory, and restore historical defense margins. It's an optimistic but plausible turnaround scenario.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">12%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury is 4.18%. Boeing's execution risk is currently extreme. Quality control issues, union negotiations, and supply chain fragility warrant a substantial risk premium. 12% is a highly punitive rate, reflecting the danger of buying into a complex restructuring.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">3.0%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Commercial aerospace is a global duopoly tied to global GDP and passenger travel growth. 3% assumes Boeing maintains its market share against Airbus long-term without aggressive pricing power, simply riding global economic expansion.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows (Turnaround Scenario)</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (Normalized)</td>
          <td>${normalizedBaseFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.030)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (12% − 3.0%))</td>
