  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Because we are making bold assumptions about Boeing's recovery, the valuation is highly sensitive to our inputs. If the turnaround is slower (10% growth) or riskier (14% WACC), the equity value plummets.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(0)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>Notice how severely the high debt load impacts lower-growth/higher-rate scenarios. In some models, the Enterprise Value isn't high enough to clear the $54B debt burden, leading to near-zero equity value.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>A DCF of a distressed or turnaround company is fragile. Here's what could drastically alter reality.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Rapid Defense Recovery:</strong> If Boeing Defense, Space & Security (BDS) stops taking massive fixed-price development charges, margins could snap back violently.</li>
    <li><strong>Duopoly Pricing Power:</strong> With Airbus sold out for years, a stabilized Boeing could aggressively raise prices on new aircraft orders, juicing margins beyond historical norms.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Paydown:</strong> If Boeing uses its recovery cash to aggressively retire debt, the equity value per share will rise rapidly as interest expense falls.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The $6B Base is a Mirage:</strong> We assumed Boeing can quickly reach $6B FCF. If cultural, regulatory, and supply chain issues keep FCF near zero (or negative) for years, this stock is worth vastly less.</li>
    <li><strong>Equity Dilution:</strong> Boeing may need to issue significant new equity to shore up its balance sheet and protect its credit rating, diluting existing shareholders and driving down the per-share value.</li>
    <li><strong>Market Share Erosion:</strong> Airbus continues to dominate the crucial narrowbody market (A321neo vs. MAX 10). Permanent loss of market share lowers terminal value.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why did you use a "normalized" FCF instead of the actual -$1.88B?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A DCF mathematically requires positive future cash flows. If you project growth on a negative number, it just becomes more negative. Because we believe Boeing will not burn cash forever (it would go bankrupt), we must model what a "normal" stabilized year looks like, and then discount those future positive cash flows back to today.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the discount rate so high (12%)?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Risk. Boeing carries $54 billion in debt and faces extreme operational challenges, regulatory scrutiny, and a tarnished reputation. A 12% WACC penalizes the valuation to account for the very real possibility that the turnaround fails or is severely delayed.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the Net Debt so large?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Boeing took on massive debt to survive the 737 MAX groundings (2019-2020) and the COVID-19 pandemic. This debt is a hard claim on the business. Any enterprise value we calculate must pay off bondholders before equity holders get anything.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

